The University of Toronto Sports Analytics Group defines sports analytics as "the process of using sports-related data (anything from player statistics to game day weather) to find meaningful patterns (strong correlations, hidden trends, etc.) and communicate those patterns (using graphs, charts, essays, etc.) to help make decisions". They go on to explain that there are four elements to the sports analytics framework and they are data management, analytic models, information systems, and the decision maker.

In [2]:
Image(url= "http://sportsanalytics.sa.utoronto.ca/files/2014/12/Fig1.png")
Out[2]:

These are fairly self explanatory. Analysts need to compile the initial data in the data management stage, build or adjust the appropriate models to analyze the data, extract the pertinent information and provide the information to the decision makers, and make an informed decisions. There are many ways that this information can be used. It can be used by coaches to make decisions on where to focus their efforts in weekly practice or they can use it to help decide what key positions to focus on during the draft or player signings. Owners and team managers can use analytics to look at prospective coaches as seen in the image below. On the other end of the spectrum, it can be used by fantasy leagues for predictions or for setting odds in gambling (not that I condone that behavior). There really is no limit to the what analytics can be used for to gain a competitive advantage.

In [3]:
Image("images/coaches.png")
Out[3]:

The models provided below show that based on season statistics in the National Football League, fairly accurate predictions can be made on who will win the Super Bowl. Obviously, there are a lot of outside factors that can affect a team in the playoffs that are impossible to predict such as injuries to key players. As is the case in all sports, there is never a sure thing but based on season statistics from 1970 to 2015 I have put together some models in an attempt to predict the future.

Step 1: Data Management¶

I imported data from 1970 to 2015 from https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/. Once this data was imported, the offense and defense tables had to be merged by team by year. Based on overall performance for the season through the championship game, each team was given an overall ranking for that year with number 1 being the Super Bowl champion, number 2 the loser of the Super Bowl, etc. The overall ranking was based on where the team finished in the playoffs. The teams that did not make it to the post season were ranked based on their overall record for the season. Teams that shared the same win/loss records were given the same ranking for the season (i.e. if three teams finished at 8-8 and they would have been ranked 15, 16, and 17, then all three were ranked 15 and the next team was ranked 18 and so on). This was done for each year and the overall ranking for each year is what will be used for the y-variable in the regression models.

To run the data through regression models, first the appropriate packages need to be imported.

2. Analytic Models¶

Next the variables are put into different linear regression models. There are multiple models that can be used including ordinary least squares, lasso, ridge, and elasticnet.

Least Squares Model using all available X-variables¶

The data is put into the Least Squares Model and the output below shows the coefficient for each X-variable along with the y-intercept.

# calculate Mean Square Error (MSE) of the predictions
# i is already the difference between Y in the MSE formula above so we simply square it. Then the sum of the squares is divided
# by the number of predictions (which is count)
mse = 0
count = 0
for i in predict['Difference']:
    count += 1
    mse += (i*i)
linearmodel1_mse = float(mse) / float(count)
print '%s %s' %("linearmodel1 Mean Square Error: ", "%.3f" % linearmodel1_mse)

linearmodel1 Mean Square Error:  40.719

Lasso Model using all available X-variables¶

Next the same thing is done but using a Lasso (least absolute shrinkage and selection operator) model. The Lasso Model performs both variable selection and regularization in order to enhance the prediction accuracy and interpretability of the statistical model it produces. This helps reduce error due to some highly correlated X-variables.

In [32]:

Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE)¶

We can also use RFE to assign weights to the coefficients of the X-Variables. The variables are then sorted by rank. This can help when selecting what X-variables to use.
Feature ranking with recursive feature elimination explained by http://scikit-learn.org: "Given an external estimator that assigns weights to features (e.g., the coefficients of a linear model), the goal of recursive feature elimination (RFE) is to select features by recursively considering smaller and smaller sets of features."

In [81]:
lr = lm.LinearRegression()
rfe = RFE(lr, n_features_to_select=2)
rfe_y = rfe.fit(X,y)

print "Features sorted by their rank:"
print sorted(zip(map(lambda x: x, rfe.ranking_), X.columns))

R Squared is a measure which tells us how well our regression equation explains observed data values.
R Squared = ( Explained Variation in Observed Values) / (Total variation in Observed Values)

0% < = R-Squared <= 100%

# load the 2016 season overall rangings and put it into a dataframe
actual2 = pd.read_csv("data/2017rank.csv")

# Sort the predict chart by "Predicted overall". This ranks the teams by predicted regular season finish.
predict9 = predict9.sort_values(by=["Predicted Overall"], ascending=[True])

# Create a new column named "Predicted Rank". This creates a column listing 1 to 32 due to the predicted rankings
# lack of whole number structure
predict9 = predict9.reset_index()
predict9['Predicted Rank'] = predict9.index+1

# Delete the index column that the above code creates
del predict9['index']

# merge the predict and actual data into a table
predict9 = pd.merge(predict9, actual2, on='Team')

# create a new column that contains the percentage difference between predicted and actual overall rankings
predict9['Difference']= (predict9['Predicted Rank'] - predict9['Actual Finish'])
predict9['% Difference']= (((predict9['Predicted Rank'] - predict9['Actual Finish']) / predict9['Predicted Rank']) * 100)

# clean up the % Change column so it is more appealing and readable, eliminating the decimals
predict9['% Difference'] = predict9['% Difference'].astype(int).abs()

# calculate Mean Square Error (MSE)
mse = 0
count = 0
for i in predict9['Difference']:
    count += 1
    mse += (i*i)
linearmodel3_mse = float(mse) / float(count)

# count will give us the total number of zeros in the difference column; these are correct predictions
count9 = 0
for i in predict9['Difference']:
    if i == 0:
        count9+=1

print '%s %s' %("Number of rankings correctly predicted: ", count9)
print '%s %s' %("Mean Square Error of predictions: ", "%.3f" % linearmodel3_mse)

4. Decision¶

Based upon the results of the 2017 prediction, this model could probably most easily be used for anyone who likes to gamble. They could decide to take an early bet on the Jaguars to win the Super Bowl and possibly make a little money. Again, not that I condone gambling. There is never a sure thing when it comes to sports analysis, it is simply intended to help make informed decisions.
If this information were presented to coaches, they could use the analysis to find where they are weak (i.e. do we need to improve our offense or defense, do we need to throw the ball more, do we need to work with defense more on creating turnovers) and find ways to improve whether it is signing players or focus in practice.

Note: Based upon the raw predicted values, one can also determine how "risky" a certain gamble might be. Looking at all of the different models and their predictions for the number one team, it seems like it would be a fairly low risk to put your money on the New England Patriots. Their raw value was anywhere between 0.21 and 0.90 while the predicted number two team had values ranging from 4.37 to 5.90. Compared to the 2017 predictions where the number one and number two values were 2.49 and 4.94, betting on the 2016 champion carries less risk than betting for 2017.
